  "method": "We propose SkillForge, a risk-controlled synthetic curriculum pipeline that replaces a fraction of real pretraining data with capability-targeted synthetic shards while guaranteeing no degradation on downstream tasks. First, define a capability graph (e.g., logical reasoning, multi-hop retrieval, code execution, spatial grounding) and attach for each node a generator–checker pair and a small, real held-out sentinel suite. For each capability, a strong teacher model produces synthetic instances targeted to that skill (e.g., question-guided prompts or programmatic templates) and emits lightweight supervision signals we can reuse during training (token logprobs/solutions/rationales). We generate diverse variants per seed (prompt paraphrases, perturbations, hard-negative distractors) and record augmentation metadata and teacher top-k logits alongside the text to enable low-overhead, replayable distillation.\n\nAll synthetic candidates are filtered by a multi-critic verifier ensemble to ensure they are valid, on-domain, and non-duplicative. Concretely, we score each item with multiple complementary critics: (1) semantic fidelity via multiple embedding models comparing input↔output consistency or solution↔spec alignment; (2) cross-model solvability via multiple base models (or smaller probes) that attempt the task; and (3) difficulty/diversity diagnostics (length, novelty vs. a real-data ANN index, error-injection success). We average/aggregate these signals into a SIM-like quality score and retain only items above a per-capability threshold, followed by near-duplicate removal and bucketed difficulty balancing. We further add a lightweight consistency regularizer during training by pairing paraphrased variants of the same synthetic item and penalizing prediction divergence to avoid overfitting to surface artifacts.\n\nAdmission of synthetic shards into training is governed by per-capability conformal risk control and advantage-gated distillation. For each capability, we periodically perform short probe updates using just the candidate shard and evaluate on its real sentinel suite to estimate the performance delta; we maintain a running, calibrated acceptance threshold that targets a maximum tolerated error increase (e.g., α = 1% per suite). Shards whose estimated risk exceeds the conformal threshold are rejected or down-weighted; accepted shards get a mixing weight that increases with estimated benefit and coverage gaps. During mixed training, we apply teacher-guided distillation only when the teacher’s advantage over the student (via confidence/margin or held-out proxy accuracy) exceeds a margin, otherwise defaulting to standard language modeling loss to prevent over-trusting erroneous synthetic supervision.\n\nTraining uses dynamic mixture scheduling: start with higher proportions of easier, high-confidence synthetic shards for each capability, then anneal toward harder ones while steadily interleaving real data. Batch composition is adjusted online using a bandit over capabilities to maximize improvement on a rotating battery of downstream probes. We keep synthetic replay cheap by storing teacher top-k logits and augmentation metadata and reusing them in the dataloader, preserving the original compute budget. Throughout, we log sequential learning curves and curriculum metadata to a centralized tracker and perform frequent A/B validations on the sentinel suites; when a capability’s synthetic stream shows diminishing returns or risk creep, its mixture weight decays automatically.\n",
  "rationale": "Targeting synthetic generation to explicit capability nodes avoids the broad distribution shifts that occur when naively swapping in generic synthetic text. Using multi-critic verification ensures that only semantically faithful, solvable, and diverse synthetic items survive to training, reducing label noise and template overfitting. The advantage-gated use of teacher signals keeps the model from inheriting teacher errors and lets the student deviate when it already performs better.\n\nMost critically, per-capability conformal admission with small real sentinel suites provides a principled safeguard: each synthetic shard must empirically clear a calibrated, data-driven threshold on real examples before it can influence training, yielding finite-sample guarantees against performance degradation. A dynamic mixture schedule then focuses compute where synthetic data is demonstrably helpful, while consistency regularization and replayable teacher logits improve learning efficiency and robustness. Together, these pieces enable replacing a measurable portion of real data with synthetic curricula without sacrificing—and often improving—downstream performance.\n",
