  "method": "Build a capability-first synthetic curriculum. Start by instantiating a capability graph that enumerates target skills (e.g., arithmetic, multi-hop reasoning, code tracing, retrieval grounding) and their dependencies. For each node, define specification-level objectives, unit tests, and minimal input–output schemas. Use constrained generators (programmatic templates, simulators, or LLMs with hard constraints) to produce synthetic items and a two-stage vetting pipeline: (1) evidence generation (rationales, intermediate steps) and (2) specification checking with external oracles (symbolic solvers, compilers, retrieval truth sets) plus reference-based metrics. Only samples that pass spec checks and show diverse coverage of the node’s decision boundary are admitted to the pool, and each sample is tagged with its capability node and difficulty.\n\nTarget where synthetic data matters most with lightweight selection and uncertainty signals. Maintain a small, continuously refreshed real holdout that reflects downstream workloads. Train a cheap selector to pick “core” synthetic examples per capability that are most likely to shift performance on the holdout, using signals from a single-pass uncertainty head and capability-coverage gaps. Sampling prioritizes: (a) high-uncertainty regions on the holdout, (b) under-covered capability nodes or edges in the graph, and (c) counterfactual pairs that separate closely confusable cases. This keeps synthetic volume low but relevant, and the selector is re-fit periodically on fresh model embeddings so the curriculum follows the model’s current failure modes.\n\nBridge the domain gap while you train. Use a representation that explicitly separates shared vs domain-specific factors between synthetic and real data, aligning the shared space and regularizing away synthetic artifacts. Interleave training with a DAgger-style correction loop: periodically roll the model on small slices of real data, capture its errors, and synthesize targeted counterexamples or demonstrations that correct those specific failure modes; mix these with a small amount of real corrections. Start with scaffolded synthetic tasks (clean, simplified, abundant feedback) and gradually remove scaffolds while increasing realism and the real:synth ratio as real-holdout metrics improve. Weight gradients by uncertainty- and quality-aware scores so reliable, high-informational synthetic items contribute more than noisy ones.\n\nEnforce no-regret gates so synthetic never degrades performance. Training proceeds in batches of synthetic updates; each batch is tentatively applied and then evaluated on the frozen real holdout. If any key metric regresses beyond a preset tolerance, the batch is rolled back or down-weighted, and its failure signature is fed back to the generator to produce harder, better-targeted items. Track coverage over the capability graph and require minimum improvements or coverage gains before advancing to harder nodes. This tight loop—spec-first generation, selective admission, aligned training with corrective rollouts, and no-regret gating—lets synthetic curricula safely replace a measurable fraction of real pretraining while improving downstream utility.\n",
  "rationale": "The approach replaces undifferentiated web-scale data with spec-checked, capability-tagged synthetic items that directly exercise the skills you care about, while a lightweight selector and uncertainty signals concentrate effort where the model is most brittle. Domain-bridged representations and a DAgger-like correction loop counteract distribution shift and overfitting to synthetic artifacts, and scaffolded-to-real scheduling mirrors how fixtures are phased out in skill learning.\n\nCritically, external specification checks and no-regret holdout gates prevent self-rewarded drift: synthetic batches must prove they help on real data before they are retained. By tracking coverage on a capability graph, the method ensures systematic growth in breadth and difficulty rather than style or fluency gains that fail to move downstream metrics. Together, these pieces enable substituting a meaningful share of real data with synthetic curricula without sacrificing—and often improving—downstream performance.\n",
